  {%- comment -%} ===== AUTHORITY STORY ===== {%- endcomment -%}
  <h2 class="advertorial__subheadline">"I Watched 300+ Spinal Surgeries. What I Saw Didn't Make Sense."</h2>

  <p class="advertorial__text">Margaret Chen spent 26 years as an orthopedic rehabilitation nurse at a major hospital system. Her job was what happened AFTER surgery. The recovery. The follow-ups. The long, slow process of finding out whether the procedure actually worked.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text"><strong>"For the first fifteen years, I didn't question anything,"</strong> she says. <strong>"The surgeon would show the MRI, point to the degeneration, and explain that the disc was compressing the nerve. It made perfect sense. Fix the structure, fix the pain."</strong></p>

  <p class="advertorial__text">Then she started noticing a pattern she couldn't explain.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text">Patients with nearly identical MRIs — same location, same severity of degeneration — were having <strong>completely different outcomes.</strong> One would recover beautifully. The next would be back in her unit six months later, same pain or worse, sometimes with new pain at adjacent segments.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text"><strong>"Same surgery. Same surgeon. Same disc. Opposite results."</strong></p>

  <p class="advertorial__text">But what haunted her most were the cancellations. Patients scheduled for surgery who tried something else in the meantime — usually in the rehabilitation unit — and <strong>improved so dramatically the surgeon postponed.</strong></p>

  <p class="advertorial__text"><strong>"I watched it happen dozens of times. And nobody could explain why."</strong></p>

  <p class="advertorial__text">That's when Margaret started asking a question that would change her understanding of chronic pain entirely: <strong>What if the degeneration on the MRI isn't the cause? What if it's the result?</strong></p>

  <hr class="advertorial__divider">

