  <h2 class="advertorial__subheadline">The Discovery That Contradicts What Most Patients Are Told</h2>

  <p class="advertorial__text">Margaret spent three years reviewing clinical research on chronic pain and inflammation. What she found shocked her.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text"><strong>Multiple peer-reviewed studies have shown that disc degeneration is present on MRIs of people with NO pain at all.</strong> In fact, research published in major medical journals found that <strong>over 50% of adults over 40 show disc degeneration on imaging — most with zero symptoms.</strong></p>

  <p class="advertorial__text">The degeneration is real. But it's not always what's generating the pain.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text">Margaret's research led her to a mechanism that most patients — and many practitioners — overlook entirely:</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text advertorial__text--highlight">Chronic deep-tissue inflammation.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text">Here's what happens: When inflammation persists in deep muscle and joint tissue for months or years, it doesn't just cause pain. <strong>It erodes.</strong> It breaks down cartilage. It narrows disc space. It creates the bone spurs and structural changes that show up on MRIs and lead surgeons to recommend intervention.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text advertorial__text--highlight">The degeneration is the scar, not the wound.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text advertorial__text--italic">Margaret compares it to a water leak in a basement. Over time, the water erodes the foundation. Cracks appear. A structural engineer looks at the cracks and says: "You need to rebuild the foundation." But if nobody fixes the leak, the water erodes the new foundation too.</p>

  <p class="advertorial__text"><strong>"That's what I watched happen for 26 years,"</strong> Margaret says. <strong>"Surgeons repairing the structural damage while the inflammatory process that caused it kept running underneath. And then everyone was surprised when the pain came back — or moved to the next segment."</strong></p>

